<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-export SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/evernote-export4.dtd">
<en-export export-date="20260611T073922Z" application="Evernote" version="11.9.1">
  <note>
    <title>Acute myeloid leukemia without differentiation (AML, M1, see Note).</title>
    <created>20220120T015524Z</created>
    <updated>20231004T135850Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Acute myeloid leukemia without differentiation (AML, M1, see Note).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic Examination:</div><div>The bone marrow shows hypercellularity with hemopoietic</div><div>components accounting for 90-95% of the marrow space, with</div><div>decrease of normal hemopoietic element. There is diffuse</div><div>infiltration of blasts accounting for more than 90% of all</div><div>nucleated cells. Megakaryocytes are depleted. No</div><div>myelofibrosis is found.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the blastic cells are positive for</div><div>CD34 immunostain, focally positive for MPO, and negative for</div><div>CD163 and CD71.</div><div>The BM aspiration also reveals hypercellular marrow with</div><div>dense blastic infiltration accounting for around 90% of all</div><div>nucleated cells. Cytoplasmic azurophilic granules and Auer</div><div>rods are occasionally found.</div><div>Promyelocytes and more mature cells are less than 10%.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: The classification of this AML is M1 based on the FAB</div><div>scheme but therapy-related AML (t-AML) associated with pre-</div><div>existing chemotherapy for breast carcinoma should be</div><div>considered.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20200303T060539Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T092351Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Aplastic anemia.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows profound hypocellularity with</div><div>predominant adipose cells. There is marked decrease of</div><div>hemopoietic element (empty marrow).</div><div>Megakaryocytes are depleted.</div><div>Few lymphoplasma cells and erythroid colonies are present.</div><div>Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of blast or</div><div>myelofibrosis is noted.</div><div><br/></div><div>The BM aspiration is dry tapping.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together the clinical &amp; hematological features,</div><div>aplastic anemia is considered.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_Hypocellular marrow without lymphoma involvement.</title>
    <created>20190312T065830Z</created>
    <updated>20190312T070207Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Hypocellular marrow without lymphoma involvement.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows hypocellularity with hemopoietic</div><div>components accounting for about 30% of the marrow space,</div><div>and an M/E ratio of 3 : 1.</div><div>The morphology, maturation process and distribution of the</div><div>three lineages are within normal limits.</div><div>Megakaryocytes are decreased in quantity but normal in</div><div>morphology. Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of</div><div>blast or myelofibrosis is noted. No atypical lymphoid cell</div><div>is identified, demonstrated by CD20 immunostain.</div><div>The BM smear shows normocellularity (30-40%) with a normal</div><div>M/E ratio. No atypical lymphocyte is noted.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_Inadequate specimen</title>
    <created>20190312T064524Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T091919Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div>Inadequate specimen</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows only few hematopoietic component,</div><div>which is inadequate for diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The bone marrow shows empty marrow without hematopoietic component, which is inadequate for diagnosis. The bone marrow aspiration (C__) reveals dry tapping. CD138 reveals no positive cells. Re-biopsy is recommended.</div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_inadequate specimen (osteosclerosis)</title>
    <created>20181226T053227Z</created>
    <updated>20181226T053332Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Bone marrow, ___ iliac crest, core biopsy --- inadequate specimen (osteosclerosis)</div><div><br/></div><div>Ref:</div><div>CBC: WBC: __ K/uL; Hb: _ g/dL; Platelet: _K/uL; blast: __%.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows osteosclerotic bony trabeculae with few hematopoietic component, which is inadequate for diagnosis. CD34 reveals no excess of blasts.</div><div>The BM aspiration is dry tapping. No evidence of malignancy is found. Re-biopsy is recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_MM</title>
    <created>20190312T070115Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T092354Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Plasma cell myeloma, histologic stage III.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows hypocellularity with hemopoietic components accounting for about 40% of the marrow space,</div><div>with depletion of normal hemopoietic elements. Megakaryocytes are depleted in this specimen.</div><div>There is dense infiltration and aggregation of plasma cells, which are positive for CD138. CD3 and CD20 immunostains</div><div>reveal no other T-cell or B-cell component. Lambda light chain restriction is further identified.</div><div>Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of blast or myelofibrosis is noted.</div><div>The BM smear shows normocellularity (~40%) with a dense plasmacytic infiltrate accounting for 70-80% of all</div><div>nucleated cells. Together with the clinical features, a plasma cell myeloma with lambda M protein is considered.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_MM (孔)</title>
    <created>20210917T013535Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T091858Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Bone marrow, ___ iliac crest, biopsy --- Plasma cell myeloma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic Examination:</div><div>The bone marrow tissue shows nearly normocellularity with hemopoietic components accounting for around 30-40% of the</div><div>marrow space, with decreased normal hemopoietic elements. Megakaryocytes are normal in quantity but atypical in</div><div>morphology. There is interstitial infiltration of plasma cells (40-50 % ) with variable maturation highlighted by</div><div>CD138 stain, which show lambda light chain restriction on kappa and lambda stains. There is minimal infiltration of</div><div>CD3-positive and CD20-positive lymphocytes. The BM aspiration also reveals increased plasma cells (30-</div><div>40%) with variable maturation and flame cell features, which are characterized by irregular cytoplasmic projections</div><div>with purple-red staining, consistent with IgA monoclonal gammopathy.</div><div><br/></div><div>Ancillary studies: Kappa, CD20, CD3, Lambda, CD138.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_normal</title>
    <created>20170718T031105Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T091916Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Normocellular marrow with trilineage hematopoiesis,</div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The specimen is composed of       piece of        tissue, measuring</div><div><br/></div><div>All are embedded in one cassette.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>1. Cellularity: 70%, normocellular for age</div><div><br/></div><div>2. Topographic distrbution: normal</div><div><br/></div><div>3.                Morphology      Number          Maturation</div><div>Myeloid        Normal          Adequate        Complete</div><div>Erythroid      Normal          Adequate        Complete</div><div>Megakaryocytes Normal          Increased</div><div><br/></div><div>4. Megakaryocyte aggregates: absent</div><div>5. Lymphoid aggregates: absent</div><div>6. Plasma cells: not increased</div><div>7. Iron: slightly increased</div><div><br/></div><div>Comments:</div><div>Fragmented subcortical normocellular marrow with maturing trilineage</div><div>hematopoiesis. No granulomas,  lymphoid  aggregates  or  metastatic  tumor </div><div>identified.  The  number of megakaryocytes  is  slightly increased, most likely</div><div>due to a compensatory reaction to peripheral destruction/consumption. No   </div><div>morphologic  evidence  of  hematopoietic malignancy.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>BM_normal 2</title>
    <created>20170718T031142Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T091909Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Hypercellular Hypocellular Normocellular marrow without lymphoma involvement, bone marrow, iliac crest, biopsy</div><div><br/></div><div>REFERENCE:</div><div>1.                             </div><div>2.                   WBC     K, Hb    , MCV    , Platelet    K, Band     %, Seg    %, Lym     %, Mono     %, Eosin      %, Baso     %, Myelocyte     %, Metamyelocyte    %, atypical Lym     %, Blast    %, NRBC     /100 WBC.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The specimen is              marrow cores measuring up to     x     x     cm.</div><div>The specimen is totally embedded in one cassette after decalcification in the Osteosoft solution.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The biopsy core is cores are normocellular with  % cellularity and normal trilineage</div><div>hematopoiesis.</div><div><br/></div><div>There is no fibrosis, granuloma, bony change nor evidence of lymphoma involvement.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical staining with anti-CD3 and anti-CD20 reveal scattered small T and B lymphocytes, excluding marrow involvement by malignant lymphoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Dr. Shih-Sung Chuang concurs with this diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>SPECIAL STAIN GROUP II:</div><div>Prussian blue stain is negative indicating depleted iron storage.</div><div>Prussian blue stain is positive indicating substantial iron storage.</div><div>Prussian blue stain is focally and weakly positive indicating low iron storage.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY: CD3, CD20</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Burkitt lymphoma</title>
    <created>20190503T001142Z</created>
    <updated>20190503T001211Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show Burkitt lymphoma mainly involving from mucosa</div><div>into the nonperitonealized perimuscular tissue (mesentery)</div><div>with focal ulceration. The tumor cells are monomorhpic</div><div>medium-sized cells with non-cleaved round nuclei, coarse</div><div>chromatin and occasionally prominent nucleoli. Mitosis is</div><div>frequently seen. Bilateral section margins are free from</div><div>tumor invasion. Dissected lymph nodes show positive for</div><div>tumor involvement.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, these cells are diffusely positive</div><div>for CD20, CD10, bcl-6 and c-MYC, focally and weakly positive</div><div>for bcl-2, but negative for CD3, CD5, cyclin D1 and MUM-1.</div><div>The Ki-67 proliferation index is around 100%. EBER in situ</div><div>hybridization is negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>ref. S0803351</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Castleman disease</title>
    <created>20170428T081345Z</created>
    <updated>20170428T081445Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Castleman disease, hyalin-vascular type, left neck lymph nodes, excision</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDINGS:</div><div>Section shows nodal structure with increased lymphoid follicles with thickened mantle</div><div>zones, small germinal centers and focal hyaline deposit. Increased number of vessels</div><div>in interfollicular spaces is seen. Some plasma cells are seen within interfollicular</div><div>regions.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, CD3, CD5, CD20, CD79a and CD43 demonstrate normal distribution</div><div>of T and B lymphocytes. The lymphoid cells of germinal center are highlighted by CD10</div><div>and bcl-6, and are negative for bcl-2. Stainings for CD21 reveal the follicular</div><div>dendritic meshworks. Staining for kappa and lambda show a polytypic pattern of plasma</div><div>cells within interfollicular region. IgD highlights the thickened mantle zone, which</div><div>is negative for IgM. The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 is high in the</div><div>germinal centers and low in the interfollicular areas. Staining for cyclin D1 is</div><div>negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>In conclusion, this is Castleman disease, hyalin-vascular type,</div><div>without evidence of malignancy.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CHL_lymphocyte-rich</title>
    <created>20170111T090317Z</created>
    <updated>20170111T090338Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show a lymph node partially effaced by paracortical expansion by singly scattered large atypical lymphoid cells, some with bi-nucleation, in a background of small lymphocytes with some residual lymphoid follicles. These atypical large cells </div><div>show huge nuclei with prominent eosinophilic nucleoli corresponding to Hodgkin and Reed-Sternberg cells. Some mummified cells are also present. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, these large cells display membrane and perinuclear dot positivity for CD30 and CD15 (focal), and nuclear positivity for MUM1 and Pax5 (weak). Stainings for CD3, CD20 and CD45 are all negative. CD21 highlights the residual </div><div>follicular dendritic meshworks. </div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a classical Hodgkin lymphoma, lymphocyte-rich subtype.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Chronic idiopathic myelofibrosis with extramedullary</title>
    <created>20170815T052357Z</created>
    <updated>20170815T052433Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show that the spleen is totally altered by extramedullary hematopoiesis with all three lineages of hematopoietic cells within the splenic cords and sinuses. There is an area of prominent fibrosis corresponding to the grossly firm and dark brownish mass.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Chronic passive congestion, consistent with clinically hypersplenism [Spleen]</title>
    <created>20180710T095640Z</created>
    <updated>20180710T100042Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Chronic passive congestion, consistent with clinically hypersplenism</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show expanded and hypocellular red pulp  with</div><div>dilated sinuses and areas of hemorrhage. The white pulp is</div><div>inconspicuous.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20221128T085049Z</created>
    <updated>20221129T021452Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Classic Hodgkin lymphoma, mixed cellularity subtype.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show four lymph nodes and other fragmented nodal tissue effaced by singly scattered large atypical lymphoid cells, some with bi-nucleation, in a background of small lymphocytes, plasma cells and histiocytes. These atypical large cells show huge nuclei with prominent eosinophilic nucleoli corresponding to Hodgkin and Reed-Sternberg cells. Some mummified cells are also present.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, these large cells display membrane</div><div>and perinuclear dot positivity for CD30 and CD15, and are positive for MUM1 and weakly positive for Pax5.</div><div>Stainings for ALK, CD3, CD20 and CD45 are negative.</div><div>In situ hybridization for EBV-encoded RNA (EBER) is negative. Only few fibrous band is demonstrate by Masson Trichrome stain.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a classical Hodgkin lymphoma, mixed</div><div>cellularity subtype.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>consistent with MGUS</title>
    <created>20190312T061729Z</created>
    <updated>20190829T013747Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div>Hypocellular marrow without evidence of myeloma.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows hypocellularity with hemopoietic components accounting for about 10% of the marrow space, and an M/E ratio of 1:1. The morphology, maturation process and distribution of the three lineages are within normal limits. Megakaryocytes are decreased in quantity and atypia in morphology.</div><div><br/></div><div>There is interstitial infiltration of plasma cells accounting for about 5-10% of mononuclear cells.</div><div>No light chain restriction is identified. Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of blast or</div><div>myelofibrosis is noted.</div><div><br/></div><div>The BM aspiration also reveals hypocellular marrow. The morphology is consistent with MGUS.</div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The bone marrow shows hypocellularity with hemopoietic components accounting for 0-30% of the marrow space, and M/E ratio of 3:1. Megakaryocytes are decreased in quantity and atypical in morphology. There are increased mature plasma cells (5-10%), highlighted by immunostain with CD138. No light chain restriction is noted by kappa and lambda stains (kappa:lambda=2-3:1). CD3 stains a few cells and CD20-positive cells are negligible. Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of blast or myelofibrosis is noted. The bone marrow aspiration (C1080850) shows hypocellular marrow with scattered plasma cells. Taken together with the clinical history, monoclonal</div><div>gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS) is considered.</div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Dermatopathic lymphadenitis</title>
    <created>20161222T011110Z</created>
    <updated>20190118T094205Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>dermatopathic lymphadenitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows paracortical aggregates of histiocytes, dendritic cells and Langerhans cells, _some containing melanin. Immunohistochemically, CD1a highlights the Langerhan cells in this area.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DLBCL vs BL, FISH will be performed</title>
    <created>20161110T145120Z</created>
    <updated>20201020T130656Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>COMMENTS: The differential diagnoses of this high-grade B-cell lymphoma include diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL), Burkitt lymphoma (BL), and unclassifiable B-cell lymphoma with features between DLBCL and BL. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) will be performed and the results with updated diagnosis will be issued as addendum. </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DLBCL, activated B-cell type, EBV-negative</title>
    <created>20180919T013717Z</created>
    <updated>20211125T090340Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, activated B-cell type, EBV-negative.</div><div>Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, non-germinal center B-cell phenotype, EBV-negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>Sections show total effacement of tonsillar architecture by diffuse large B-cell lymphoma composed of large atypical</div><div>lymphocytes with round nuclei, single centrally located to several nucleoli and an appreciable amount of clear to basophilic cytoplasm. No residual follicular dendritic</div><div>network is identified by CD21 immunostain. Immunohistochemically, these cells are positive for CD20, bcl-6, MUM-1, bcl-2 and c-MYC (focal), but negative for CD3,</div><div>CD10, cyclin D1, p40, p16 and CK. The Ki67 proliferative index is around 50%. EBER in situ hybridization is negative.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DLBCL, LN</title>
    <created>20161110T144846Z</created>
    <updated>20170802T070741Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows a nodal structure diffusely effaced by atypical lymphoid cells infiltrating the adjacent adipose tissue. These atypical lymphoid cells are large-sized with vesicular nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and abundant pale to eosinophilic cytoplasm, accompanied by increased mitotic activity.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphoid cells are positive for CD20, bcl-2, c-Myc but not CD3, CD5, CD10, bcl-6, MUM-1, or cyclin D1. CD21 stain highlights the residual follicles. The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 is around 90%.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of non-germinal center B-cell phenotype.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>This is double expressor (bcl-2 and myc) diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of non-germinal  center B-cell phenotype. Dr. Shih-Sung Chuang concurs with the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Dr Shih-Sung Chuang concurs with the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDIES</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><en-media hash="96b33302252c2f58f0f3b1d213dcf626" type="image/jpeg" /></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
