  <note>
    <title>DLBCL, stomach, GC type</title>
    <created>20230106T025115Z</created>
    <updated>20230106T025442Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Stomach, antrum, endoscopic biopsy---</div><div>Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, germinal center B-cell type, EBV-negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>Sections shows gastric tissue with diffuse infiltrate of atypical lymphocytes with round nuclei, prominent nucleoli and an appreciable amount of clear to basophilic cytoplasm. Residual follicular dendritic network is demonstrated by CD21 immunostain. These atypical lymphoid cells are positive for CD20, CD10, bcl-6 but negative for CD3, and cyclin D1. Around 30% of the tumor cells labeles for c-myc immunostain. The result is considered negative using the most frequently adopted cut-off value of 40% in the literature.</div><div>The Ki67 proliferative index is high up to 95%. EBER in situ hybridization is negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>This is diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of germinal center B-cell phenotype,</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>DLBCL, stomach, non-GC</title>
    <created>20191025T025041Z</created>
    <updated>20230607T060157Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-size: 11px;"><span style="color:rgb(39, 65, 128);">Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, stomach, biopsy</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 11px;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 11px;"><span style="color:rgb(39, 65, 128);">Section shows necrotic debris indicating ulceration. The gastric mucosal tissue is effaced by atypical lymphocytes in a diffuse pattern. These atypical lymphocytes are medium to large-sized with frequent mitoses. There is no lymphoepithelial lesion or H.pylori.</span></span></div><div><span style="font-size: 11px;"><span style="color:rgb(39, 65, 128);">Immunohistochemically, these atypical lymphocytes express CD20, bcl-2, bcl-6, and MUM1 but not CD3, CD10, or cyclin D1. MYC is positive in around 40% cells, and is considered to be positive by the current criterion of 40% as the cutoff. The staining for CD21 is negative for follicular dendritic meshworks. The proliferation fraction as determined by Ki-67 is at 90%.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 11px;"><span style="color:rgb(39, 65, 128);">In situ hybridization for EBV-encoded mRNA (EBER) is negative.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 11px;"><span style="color:rgb(39, 65, 128);">This is diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of non-germinal center B-cell phenotype, and also a double expressor.</span></span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>EBV, EBER</title>
    <created>20161110T145054Z</created>
    <updated>20230626T075616Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>In situ hybridization for EBV-encoded RNA (EBER) is positive only in _</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Empty marrow (see Note). suspect AA</title>
    <created>20200619T071144Z</created>
    <updated>20230721T092345Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Empty marrow (see Note).</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows empty marrow with hemopoietic components accounting for &lt;5% of the marrow space with</div><div>decrease of hemopoietic elements. Megakaryocytes are depleted. Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of blast or</div><div>myelofibrosis is noted. No evidence of lymphoma/metastasis is noted.</div><div>The BM aspiration also reveals hypocellular marrow with an M/E ratio of 2-3:1. No evidence of myelodysplasia is found.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: If the specimen is representative, aplastic anemia should be considered. Otherwise, follow-up is recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Extramedullary hematopoiesis (EMH)</title>
    <created>20161201T044706Z</created>
    <updated>20161201T044755Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Hemopoietic cell lineages, including granulocytic cells (MPO+), erythropoietic cells (CD71+) and megakaryocytes (CD61+), are noted.  </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Extramedullary hematopoiesis, spleen</title>
    <created>20170405T014431Z</created>
    <updated>20170405T014457Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show that the spleen is totally altered by extramedullary hematopoiesis with</div><div>all three lineages of hematopoietic cells within the splenic cords and sinuses.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Follicular lymphoma (LN)</title>
    <created>20161110T144909Z</created>
    <updated>20170316T063707Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Sections show nodal architecture totally effaced by closely-packed follicles with extension into extranodal fat. The follicles are composed predominantly of centrocytes with irregular nuclear contour admixed with some centroblasts featuring medium- to large-sized, vesicular nuclei and distinct small nucleoli.</div>
<div>
<div><br/></div>
<div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphoid cells express _. CD21 highlights the follicular dendritic meshworks in the neoplastic follicles. The proliferation index demonstrated by Ki-67 is is around _%.</div>
<div><br/></div>
<div>Taken together, this is a _-grade or grade _ follicular lymphoma.</div>
<div><br/></div>
<div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDIES:</div>
<div><br/></div>
<div><br/></div>
</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Follicular lymphoma, grade 1 (LN)</title>
    <created>20170316T063648Z</created>
    <updated>20250930T055735Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show nodal architecture totally effaced by closely-packed follicles. High</div><div>magnification of the follicles show that most lymphocytes are small centrocytes</div><div>admixed with occasional centroblasts, consistent with follicular lymphoma grade 1.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphoid cells express CD10, CD20, bcl-2 and bcl-6</div><div>but not CD3, MUM-1 or cyclin D1. Immunostains for CD21, CD23 and CD35 highlight</div><div>follicular dendritic cell meshworks within neoplastic follicles. The proliferation</div><div>index demonstrated by Ki-67 is is around 30%.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a low-grade or grade 1 follicular lymphoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDIES: CD3, CD10, CD20, CD21, CD23, CD35, bcl-2, bcl-6, Ki-67,</div><div>MUM1, cyclin D1.</div><div><br/></div><div><a href="evernote:///view/26224745/s227/e03d18c2-6046-ffa8-4ee9-4d7d484a8125/d34eea68-cb9f-441a-bbbb-275eb7796b2a">Follicular lymphoma</a></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Follicular lymphoma, low grade, biopsy</title>
    <created>20161110T144951Z</created>
    <updated>20161110T145004Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>(Biopsy, low-grade FL) Section shows tissue cores composed of atypical lymphocytes in vague nodular pattern with stromal sclerosis. These atypical lymphocytes are composed predominantly of centrocytes with irregular nuclear contour admixed with some centroblasts featuring medium- to large-sized, vesicular nuclei and distinct small nucleoli. Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphocytes are positive for CD10, CD20, bcl-2 and  bcl-6, but not CD3 or cyclin D1. CD21 highlights the follicular dendritic meshworks. The proliferation index demonstrated by Ki-67 is around 20%.  Taken together, this is a low-grade or grade 2 follicular lymphoma.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Hypersplenism</title>
    <created>20161201T044813Z</created>
    <updated>20161201T044823Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show preserved splenic architecture in most areas with markedly expanded red pulps, widening of splenic cords, and congestion in cords and sinuses. These findings are compatible with 

<span style="font-family:gotham, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;font-size:14px;">hypersplenism</span>

. </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Inadequate specimen (see Note)</title>
    <created>20251013T063324Z</created>
    <updated>20251013T063446Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Bone marrow, iliac crest, biopsy ---</div><div>Inadequate specimen (see Note)</div><div><br/></div><div>This case had been sent to Dr. Kung-Chao Chang at National</div><div>Cheng Kung University Hospital for further consultation</div><div><br/></div><div>Gross description:</div><div>The specimen consists of a piece of tissue measuring</div><div>0.3x0.2x0.2 cm.</div><div><br/></div><div>All for section after decalcification.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows fibrous and bony tissue only. No marrow</div><div>component is identified.</div><div>The bone marrow smears also show dry tapping but some</div><div>hypersegmented neutrophils and mast cells are noted.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note:</div><div>This specimen is insufficient for diagnosis. Although megaloblastic anemia might be impressed, re-biopsy is highly recommended.</div><div><br/></div><div>Ref: S1409231</div><div>CBC/DC (114/8/24): WBC: 3200/uL; Hb: 10.6 g/dL; MCV: 104.3</div><div>fL; Platelet: 117K/uL; blast: 0; Neu: 85.0%; Lym: 10.0%.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Kappa, lambda (Benign/inconclusive)</title>
    <created>20161215T081038Z</created>
    <updated>20241121T073143Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: Calibri;"><span style="font-size: 14pt;">These plasma cells are polytypic for kappa and lambda light chains.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: Calibri;"><span style="font-size: 14pt;">Kappa and lambda stains are inconclusive for the determination of light chain</span></span></div><div><span style="font-family: Calibri;"><span style="font-size: 14pt;">restriction.</span></span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Kikuchi&apos;s disease (Histiocytic necrotizing lymphadenitis)</title>
    <created>20161110T145015Z</created>
    <updated>20161222T010500Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Section shows fragmented lymphoid tissue with patchy areas of necrosis within the paracortex with numerous karyorrhectic nuclear debris surrounded by a mixture of mononuclear cells and histiocytes.</div>
<div>Immunohistochemically, stainings for CD3 and CD20 reveal normal distribution of T and B lymphocytes. CD21 highlights the follicular dendritic meshworks in lymphoid follicles. The mononuclear cells adjacent to the necrotic areas are positive for MPO. The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 shows no significant increase.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Lab Reference</title>
    <created>20151215T023003Z</created>
    <updated>20170606T004430Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>-- WBC _/uL, Band _%, Seg _%, Lym_%, Mono_%, Eosin _%, Baso _%, atypical lymphocyte _%, Hb _g/dL, PLT _/uL,</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20180928T092456Z</created>
    <updated>20190213T084041Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Lymphoid hyperplasia with clusters of epithelioid histiocytes &amp; monocytoid lymphocytes, suggesting infectious lymphadenitis (see Note).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show follicular and interfollicular hyperplasia with capsular and intra-lymphoid fibrosis. Collection of epithelioid histiocytes, encroaching upon or within the germinal centers &amp; hyperplasia of monocytoid lymphocytes are present. Central suppurative inflammation is found in some granulomas. Expansion of histiocytes with foamy cytoplasm is also identified.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the mixed inflammatory background is mixed positive for CD3 and CD20. CD68 and S100 highlight small granulomas and hyperplastic histiocytes. Spirochete immunostain is negative. Acid-fast, TB immunostain &amp; PAS stains fail to reveal any specific etiology. IgG4-positive cells are few. Toxoplasma immunostain and EBER in situ hybridization are both negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: The histologic features suggest infection and toxoplasmic lymphadenitis or other pathogens should be considered first. Correlation with serologic studies is necessary.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>ref: SF0800536</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>MALT lymphoma, parotid gland</title>
    <created>20170413T065359Z</created>
    <updated>20240322T023811Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>https://www.google.com.tw/search?sourceid=chrome-psyapi2&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;q=malt%20lymphoma&amp;oq=MALT%20lymphoma&amp;aqs=chrome.0.69i59j0l5.1872j0j7</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphomas</div><div><br/></div><div>Sections show a mass composed of dense infiltrate of atypical lymphocytes infiltrating to adjacent fat, with lymphoepithelial lesion and residual salivary gland acini and </div><div>ducts. Expanded lymphoid follicles with follicular colonization are also seen. The atypical lymphocytes are small to medium-sized with mild nuclear irregularity and</div><div>clear cytoplasm. The surrounding lymph nodes are also partially effaced by atypical lymphocytes, with focal increase of plasma cells. The adjacent salivary gland</div><div>shows lymphoepithelial sialadenitis with presence of lymphoepithelial islands.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, staining for CK (AE1/AE3) highlightes the lymphoepithelial lesion. The atypical lymphocytes are positive for CD20, but not CD3, CD21 or cyclin</div><div>D1. The CD21 staining highlights the expanded and disrupted follicular dendritic meshowarks. The proliferation fraction as determined by Ki-67 is around 10%. The</div><div>plasma cells are polytypic for both lambda and kappa light chain expression, suggesting reactive hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma with nodal involvement.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>MALT lymphoma, stomach</title>
    <created>20170425T061206Z</created>
    <updated>20190912T145958Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows gastric mucosa infiltrated by atypical lymphocytes in a vaguely nodular</div><div>pattern. Lymphoepithelial lesions are noted focally. The atypical lymphocytes are</div><div>small to medium-sized with slightly irregular nuclei, moderately dispersed chromatin,</div><div>inconspicuous nucleoli, and pale cytoplasm.</div><div><br/></div><div>Warthin Starry stain is negative for Helicobacter.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, these atypical lymphocytes express CD20 and bcl-2, but not CD3,</div><div>CD10, bcl-6, cyclin D1, or IgD. Staining for cytokeratin highlights the</div><div>lymphoepithelial lesions. The proliferation fraction by Ki-67 immunostaining is low.</div><div>CD21 highlights expanded and distorted follicular dendritic cell meshworks.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Metastasis, totally effaced</title>
    <created>20170301T084414Z</created>
    <updated>20170301T084434Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show soft tissue infiltrated by neoplastic __ cells with invasion into skeletal muscle fibers. Although no  residual lymphoid tissue is discernible, this metastatic lesion might represent a nodal metastasis with totally destroyed nodal architecture.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Myc</title>
    <created>20161110T145201Z</created>
    <updated>20161110T145206Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Around 20% of the tumor cells labeles for c-myc immunostain. The result is considered negative using the most frequently adopted cut-off value of 40% in the literature.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Mycosis fungoides</title>
    <created>20170707T052911Z</created>
    <updated>20170707T052913Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>, skin, right thigh, biopsy</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>REFERENCE:</div><div><br/></div><div>20200400</div><div>1. Mycosis fungoides, skin, back, upper, rash area, biopsy</div><div>2. Mycosis fungoides, skin, back, lower, brownish area, biopsy</div><div>2014031704</div><div>Mycosis fungoides, skin, back, biopsy</div><div>2013121281</div><div>1. Mycosis fungoides, skin, back, biopsy</div><div>2. Mycosis fungoides, skin, back, biopsy</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The specimen is composed of one piece of skin tissue, measuring 0.4 x 0.3 x 0.3 cm.</div><div><br/></div><div>All are embedded in one cassette.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>Sections show skin tissue with atypical lymphocyes infiltrate in the upper dermis</div><div>and around the blood vessels in deep dermis and superficial subcutis. The epidermis is involved by atypical lymphocytes in single cell or in small clusters and haloed lymphocytes in the basal layer. The atypical lymphocytes are small sized with slighly irregular nuclear contours.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphocytes are</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken clinical information and pathologic features together, this is consistent</div><div>with mycosis fungoides.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STAINS:</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20200527T060003Z</created>
    <updated>20200527T060044Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Myelodysplastic syndrome without excess of blasts.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The bone marrow shows hypocellularity with hemopoietic components accounting for about 30% of the marrow space, and M/E ration of 1-2: 1 on MPO staining. The morphology,</div><div>maturation process and distribution of the three lineages are dysplastic. Megakaryocytes are decreased in quantity and dysplastic in morphology on CD61 stain. No evidence of</div><div>excess of blast or myelofibrosis is noted. CD34 stain reveals no excess of blasts. The bone marrow aspiration also reveals hypocellular marrow</div><div>with myelodysplastic changes. No excess of blasts is found. </div><div>Taken together the clinical &amp; hematological features, myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS) without excess of blasts is considered.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Myeloid sarcoma</title>
    <created>20170117T011100Z</created>
    <updated>20170117T011132Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show _ tissue infiltrated by medium-sized, monotonous cells featuring scant cytoplasm, round or folded nuclei, fine</div><div>chromatin and small nucleoli. Necrosis and numerous mitotic figures are seen. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the myeloblasts are positive for CD34, MPO, CD163 and CD117. The proliferation index is high in tumor cells.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20191022T013207Z</created>
    <updated>20191022T013226Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div>Myeloid sarcoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows mammary tissue cores infiltrated by diffuse</div><div>sheets of rounded to oval neoplastic cells with occasional</div><div>nodular aggregates. The neoplastic cells exhibit</div><div>finely granular chromatin and scant to moderate amount of</div><div>cytoplasm.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical study shows the neoplastic cells are</div><div>strongly positive for CD34 and MPO. Stainings for CD45 and</div><div>CD117 are weakly positive. Stainings for CK, CD3, and</div><div>CD20, TdT are negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>This is myeloid sarcoma. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Please correlate with clinical</div><div>history to exclude therapy-related myeloid neoplasm.</div><div><br/></div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Non-M3 acute myeloid leukemia</title>
    <created>20170718T030927Z</created>
    <updated>20180621T055906Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Non-M3 acute myeloid leukemia, bone marrow, iliac crest, biopsy</div><div><br/></div><div>CLINICAL INFORMATION: r/o leukemia</div><div><br/></div><div>HEMOGRAM:</div><div>WBC _K, Hb _, MCV _, Plt _K, Band 0%, Seg _%, Lym _%, Mono _%, Eos _%, Baso _%, Blast _%, NRBC _/100WBC.</div><div><br/></div><div>GROSS DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The specimen is four marrow cores measuring up to _ x _ x _ cm.</div><div>The specimen is totally embedded in one cassette after decalcification in the</div><div>Osteosoft solution. There is no fibrosis, granuloma, nor bony change.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINGDINGS:</div><div>The biopsy core is hypercellular with 60% cellularity and decreased normal trilineage</div><div>hematopoiesis. Myeloid cells show left-shifted maturaation with around 30% of marrow</div><div>cells are immature cells. The number of erythroblasts is decreased, while the</div><div>distribution and morphology of megakaryocytes are essentially unremarkable.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical study shows that the immature cells express CD34 and CD117. CD61,</div><div>CD71 and MPO stainings highlight megakaryocytes, erythroblasts and mature myeloid</div><div>cells, respectively. These findings indicate non-M3 acute myeloid leukemia, most</div><div>likely AML-M2.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>SPECIAL STAIN GROUP II:</div><div>1. Prussian blue stain is positive indicating substantial iron storage.</div><div>2. Reticulin stain shows a normal reticulin pattern without myelofibrosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMICAL STUDY: CD34, CD61, CD71, CD117, MPO.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20221209T060509Z</created>
    <updated>20221209T060811Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>plasma cell myeloma.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>The decalcified section shows fractures of bony spicules</div><div>with infiltration and aggregation of plasma cells with</div><div>variable maturation, which are highlighted by CD138 and</div><div>MUM1. Kappa light chain restriction is identified on kappa</div><div>and lambda stains.</div><div><br/></div><div>Together with the clinical features, a plasma cell myeloma</div><div>is considered.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Plasmacytoma</title>
    <created>20160822T090303Z</created>
    <updated>20161117T023209Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows fracture of bony trabeculae infiltrated by sheets of relatively 
monotonous tumor cells featuring eccentrically located nuclei with stippled chromatin patterns and basophilic cytoplasm.
</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for CD20, CD79a, CD138, MUM-1, and cyclin D1 but not CD3, CD19 or AE1/AE3, and are monotypic for kappa light chain. They are negative for lambda light chain. 
</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a plasmacytoma. Systemic survey is mandatory to rule out 
</div><div>multiple myeloma.
</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Plasmacytoma, bone</title>
    <created>20161202T011804Z</created>
    <updated>20200923T070912Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>DIAGNOSIS: </div><div>Plasmacytoma</div><div><br/></div><div>Section shows bony spicules infiltrated by sheets of relatively monotonous tumor cells featuring eccentrically located nuclei with stippled chromatin patterns and basophilic cytoplasm.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells express CD138 diffusely and are monotypic for kappa /  lambda light chain. They are negative for _ light chain.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is a plasmacytoma. Systemic survey is mandatory to rule out multiple myeloma.</div><div><br/></div><div>IMMUNOHISTOCHEMISTRY: CD138, kappa and lambda light chains.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20211012T071035Z</created>
    <updated>20211012T071055Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Primary cutaneous CD4-positive small/medium T-cell lymphoproliferative disorder.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a relatively circumscribed lymphoproliferation in the dermis and superficial subcutaneous fat without epidermotropism. The infiltrate is in a diffuse pattern and is composed predominantly of small to medium lymphocytes, with scattered large cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical study shows that most of the lymphocytes are T-cells expressing CD2, CD3, CD4, and BF1 but not CD8, CD10, CD20, TIA-1, PD-1, ICOS, or TCR-delta.</div><div>Scattered cells express bcl-6, CD25 and CD30. The labeling index by Ki67 is at around 20-30%. In situ hybridization for EBV is negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>This is primary cutaneous CD4-positive small/medium T-cell lymphoproliferative disorder.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Primary mediastinal large B-cell lymphoma</title>
    <created>20170512T111503Z</created>
    <updated>20170514T232922Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><font face="Gulim">Primary mediastinal large B-cell lymphoma</font></div><div><font face="Gulim">Section shows atypical lymphoid cells in diffuse <font style="font-family: Gulim;">pattern partially surrounded by fibrosis. </font>The atypical lymphoid cells are large-sized with pale cytoplasm and fine sclerosis compartmentalizing the tumor cells, i<font style="font-family: Gulim;">n a background of small lymphocytes. Some <font style="font-family: Gulim;">Hodgkin-like cells are present. </font></font></font></div><div><font face="Gulim"><font style="font-family: Gulim;"><font style="font-family: Gulim;"><br/></font></font></font></div><div><font face="Gulim"><font style="font-family: Gulim;"><font style="font-family: Gulim;">Immunohistochemically, t</font></font></font><span style="font-family: Gulim;">he tumor cells are positive for CD20, CD23, CD30, CD79a, bcl2, bcl6 (focal) and myc, MUM1, but not CD3, CD10 or cyclin D1</span> . <span style="font-family: Gulim;">AE1/AE3 highlight the thymic remnants which are infiltrated by tumor cells. , The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 is around 50%. </span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Progressive transformation of germinal centers (PTGC)</title>
    <created>20170202T055107Z</created>
    <updated>20170202T055128Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Some of the follicles show progressive transforation with extension of the mantle cells into the germinal centers. </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>PTCL (DDx ATLL and PTCL,NOS)</title>
    <created>20170227T024747Z</created>
    <updated>20180717T055407Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>The specimens show infiltration of diffuse sheets of atypical lymphoid cells within the lamina propria. These atypical lymphoid cells are medium-to large-sized with</div><div>irregular nuclei and brisk mitotic activity. Crushing artifacts are present.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphocytes express __. The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 immunostaining is around _%.</div><div><br/></div><div>In situ hybridization for EBV-encoded mRNA (EBER) is __.</div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is consistent with a peripheral T-cell lymphoma with the differential diagnoses of adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma and peripheral T-cell</div><div>lymphoma, not otherwise specified.</div><div><br/></div><div>A serum test for anti-HTLV is recommended to exclude the diagnosis of adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>PTCL, NOS</title>
    <created>20180717T055435Z</created>
    <updated>20180717T055454Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Peripheral T-cell lymphoma,</div><div>not otherwise specified (please see COMMENTS)</div><div><br/><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show cutaneous tissue with a diffuse atypical</div><div>lymphocytic infiltration from ulcerated epidermis to</div><div>subcutaneous layer. The infiltrate atypical lymphocytes are</div><div>medium-sized with fine chromatin, small nucleoli and high</div><div>N/C ratio, resulting a blastic appearance. Frequent mitoses</div><div>are seen and geographic necrosis is focally noted. There is</div><div>no epidermotropism.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical lymphocytes express CD3</div><div>and CD45 but not CD4, CD5, CD8, CD20, CD25, CD30, TdT, CD1a,</div><div>CD34, MPO, TIA-1, granzyme B, BF-1 or TCR-gamma. No</div><div>follicular dentritic meshwork is highlighted by CD21. The</div><div>labeling index by Ki67 is up to 80%. In situ hybridization</div><div>for EBV-encoded mRNA (EBER) is negative.</div><div><br/></div><div>In conclusion, this is PTCL-NOS.</div><div><br/></div><div>COMMENTS:</div><div>Although adult T-cell lymphoma is among the differentials,</div><div>it is unlikely as the tumor cells are negative for CD4 and</div><div>CD25. Please correlate with the HTLV-1 status. If the</div><div>serum is positive for anti-HTLV, this is adult T-cell</div><div>leukemia/lymphoma with unsual phenotype. If negative, this</div><div>is peripheral T-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified</div><div>PTCL</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Reactive hyperplasia</title>
    <created>20140922T003813Z</created>
    <updated>20250815T073634Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Reactive hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows lymph nodes revealing reactive follicular hyperplasia with polarized mantle zone and geographic-shaped germinal centers which contain light and dark zones and numerous tingible body macrophages. Paracortical hyperplasia resulting a "moth-eaten" appearance is also discerned. No evidence of granuloma or malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, CD3 and CD20 demonstrate normal distribution of T and B lymphocytes.  The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 is high in the germinal centers and low in the interfollicular areas.</div><div><br/></div><div>The lymphoid cells of germinal center are negative for bcl-2.</div><div><br/></div><div>Dr. Shih-Sung Chuang concurs with this diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>IgD shows attenuated or absent mantle zone around these follicles.</div><div><br/></div><div>    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>residual acute myeloid leukemia AML</title>
    <created>20200930T060123Z</created>
    <updated>20200930T073513Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Empty marrow, but excess of blasts (10-20%) in bone marrow</div><div>smear (see Note).</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div>The bone marrow shows empty marrow without hemopoietic</div><div>components. Neither dysplasia, nor evidence of excess of</div><div>blasts or myelofibrosis can be evaluated.</div><div>CD34 staining shows no excess of<span>    </span> blasts.</div><div>However, the BM aspiration reveals hypocellular marrow with</div><div>excess of blasts (10-20%).</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: Taken together the clinical &amp; hematological features,</div><div>residual acute myeloid leukemia is considered.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20170324T093510Z</created>
    <updated>20170829T083109Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section of the punch biopsy shows a diffuse lymphocytic infiltration in the dermis by medium to large atypical lymphocytes, some cells seem to cluster within vascular spaces.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells express CD3, CD4, CD30, and MUM1 but not CD20,</div><div>CD56, CD68, CD162 (cutaneous leukocyte-associated antigen), TIA-1, granzyme B or EMA.</div><div>Stainings with CD31 and CD34 highlights endothelial cells, but there are no</div><div>intravascular tumor cells.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">Clinical correlation is mandatory to decide whether this is lymphomatoid papulosis or </span><span style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">primary cutaneous anaplatic large cell lymphoma.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Small lymphocytic lymphoma (SLL)</title>
    <created>20260212T012304Z</created>
    <updated>20260212T012324Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Small lymphocytic lymphoma (SLL). See Comment.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Section reveals lymphoid tissue in which the normal nodal</div><div>architecture is effaced by diffuse proliferation of</div><div>atypical lymphoid cells with proliferation centers.</div><div>Prolymphocytes and paraimmunoblasts are present.</div><div><br/></div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the atypical lymphoid cells are</div><div>positive for CD20, CD23, CD5, and bcl2, and negative for</div><div>CD10, and cyclin D1. EBER is negative. No follicular</div><div>dendritic meshworks are identified by CD21. Bcl6 and MUM1</div><div>are focally and weakly positive. The Ki67 proliferation</div><div>index is aound 40%.</div><div><br/></div><div>Comment:</div><div>Correlation with clinical findings is recommended to exclude</div><div>the possibility of chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL).</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>建議excision [severe crushing artifact]</title>
    <created>20180110T083632Z</created>
    <updated>20230606T094416Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>http://www.twiap.org.tw/pa/search/searchData.asp?Document_SID=9114</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="box-sizing: border-box; zoom: 1; width: 911.391px; min-height: 80px; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(17, 17, 17); line-height: 34px; vertical-align: top; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; border-bottom-color: rgb(225, 225, 225); position: relative; height: auto !important; font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">Note: Due to severe crushing artifact, no definite diagnosis can be made. Lymph node excision is recommended if clinical lymphadenopathy is present.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
</en-export>
